		  	<div class="nine columns offset-by-one">
		  	<h1>Health Matters</h1>
		</div>
	</div>
    
    <div class="row">
		<div class="ten columns offset-by-one">
		
			<p style="padding-top:20px">Adolescents occupy a very special place in the world, standing squarely between childhood and adulthood. Scientifically documented as the most tumultuous time in one’s life, adolescence can also be the ripest: Ripe for planting healthy behaviors that take root, ripe for changing unhealthy patterns into nourishing ones, ripe for guiding to healthfulness. Too often, the emotional and physical health of our adolescents takes a back seat to the needs of infants and toddlers. Yet adolescence is the most formative period in our lives for adopting behaviors that ensure good health throughout life.</p>
			
			<h2>Depression</h2>
     		<p>One of the hallmarks of adolescence is moodiness. It is usually attributed to the stress of 
			growing up and the influence of hormones and brain development. But what happens 
			when it’s more than moodiness, or when sadness lingers or worsens and interferes with 
			your everyday life? 
			<p>Depression can change the way you see yourself, your life, and the people around you. It
			can affect your feelings of self-worth, motivation, and influence your perception of 
			danger and risk. 
			<p>When you are concerned about how you are feeling, it’s okay to reach out and ask for 
			help. There are adults who want to help. If you can’t get the help you need at home, a 
			teacher, counselor, or school nurse are good people to turn to. They can help get the 
			support you need to sort things out. 
			<p>For a list of clinics and mental health providers, <a href="clinic-finder.php">click here</a></p>
			<p><b>If you need immediate help, there are resources available to you:</b></p>
			<p><b>TEEN LINE</b>: The Teen Line is a service staffed by teenage volunteers who answer phone calls, emails and chats. It’s an organization based in Southern California, but they help people all over the country. The people who run Teen Line have been specially trained to help other young people. They won’t judge you or give advice – their job is to listen to your feelings and help you to clarify your concerns, define the options available to you, and help you make positive decisions. No problem is too small, too large, or too shocking for the Teen Line volunteers.</p>
			<p>If you’d like to talk with someone like you about the issues you are facing or feelings you are having, Teen Line is a confidential telephone helpline for teenage callers. Teen Line is open every evening from 8:00 pm to 12:00 pm (Chicago time), and the call is free. If you have a problem or just want to talk with another teen who understands, then this is the right place for you!</p>
			<p>You can call Teen Line at <a href="tel:1-800-852-8336">1-800-852-8336</a> and even text them by texting “TEEN” to 839863. Teen Line also offers  <a href="http://teenlineonline.org/boards/" target="_blank">message boards</a>, resources and information. You can visit their website  <a href="http://teenlineonline.org/" target="_blank">http://teenlineonline.org/</a> for more information.</p>
			<p><b>YOU MATTER</b>: If you or someone you know is considering suicide, <b><u>do not</b></u> hesitate to reach out for help.  Don’t worry about someone getting mad, at you, getting in trouble, or that you might be wrong or overreacting. It’s not worth taking a chance on staying quiet when someone could really be having a hard time and considering hurting themselves.</p>
			<p>You Matter is an organization for teens that provides information about a 24/7 suicide hotline number and online chat for when you need to talk to someone. They also have a blog about struggling with depression and suicide, as well as links to a variety of resources around the Web to learn more about how to help yourself or a friend who is struggling with depression and suicide. Call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at <a href="tel:1-800-273-8255">1-800-273-8255</a> at any time or visit <a href="http://www.youmatter.suicidepreventionlifeline.org/" target="_blank">http://www.youmatter.suicidepreventionlifeline.org/</a> to chat online and get more information about suicide risk and prevention.</p>
			<p><b>TREVOR PROJECT</b>: For teens who may want to talk to someone who identifies as Lesbian, Bisexual, Gay, Transgender, or Questioning (LGBTQ), the Trevor Project has a 24/7 suicide prevention phone number, daily online chat, texting, and other programs to support LGBTQ youth. The Trevor Project operates Trevor Chat, Trevor Text, and Ask Trevor, which are 3 programs dedicated to reaching people in crisis. Trevor Project’s goal is to provide life-saving and life-affirming resources for LGBTQ youth and to create safe, accepting and inclusive environments for all young people, no matter what their sexual orientation or gender identity. If you or someone you know needs to talk, call the Trevor Lifeline at <b>1-866-488-7386</b> or visit <a href="http://www.thetrevorproject.org/Programs" target="_blank">http://www.thetrevorproject.org/Programs to use Trevor Chat or Ask Trevor.</a></p>
			
