				<h2>Disease Prevention</h2>
				<p>While immunizations for infants and young children are readily acknowledged as being vital to well-being, the importance of boosters and recommended vaccines for adolescents is not always recognized.&nbsp;</p>
				<p>Since 2005, new vaccines have become available and are recommended for adolescents by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Such vaccines include meningococcal (meningitis), human papillomavirus (HPV), and expanded recommendations for influenza (flu), as well as the Tdap vaccine, which expands the typical tetanus booster to include protection against pertussis (whooping cough).&nbsp;</p>
				<p>Adolescents and young adults need to continue their immunizations series and receive booster shots for ongoing protection against diseases and to help protect their families and communities by slowing or stopping disease outbreaks. &nbsp;</p>
				<p><strong>Vaccines Recommended for Adolescents&nbsp;</strong></span></p>
				<p><strong>Tdap Vaccine</strong> can prevent tetanus, diphtheria, and pertussis. It is recommended for adolescents because the immunization they received as children begins to wear off, making them more vulnerable to infection and unintentionally spreading the disease&mdash;a serious concern for babies not yet immunized.&nbsp;</span></p>
				<p>Tetanus</span> is a serious disease caused by a toxin (poison) made by bacteria that is commonly found in soil. Tetanus does not spread from person to person. The bacteria enter the body through scrapes, cuts or puncture wounds. Symptoms may include headache, feeling cranky, and muscle spasms that can cause breathing problems and paralysis. Three of ten people who get tetanus die from the disease.&nbsp;</span></p>
				<p>Diphtheria</span> is a serious disease that spreads when an infected person coughs or sneezes. Diphtheria starts with sore throat, swollen glands in the neck, low-grade fever (101 degrees or less), and chills. 
				<p>It causes a thick coating in the back of the nose or throat that makes it hard to breathe or swallow. About one out of ten people who get diphtheria will die.</span></p>
				<p>Pertussis</span>&mdash;commonly referred to as whooping cough&mdash;is a very contagious&nbsp; respiratory disease. Pertussis can cause spells of violent coughing and choking, making it hard to breathe, drink, or eat.&nbsp; Pertussis can be fatal, especially in babies less than one year of age. They are too young to receive the vaccine and rely on the immunity of those around them to protect them.</span></p>
				<p><strong>Chickenpox</strong> is caused by the virus varicella zoster, which spreads very easily from infected people.&nbsp;</span></p>
				<p>Typical symptoms include an itchy rash with blisters, tiredness, headache and fever. Chickenpox is usually mild, but it can lead to severe skin infections, pneumonia, encephalitis (brain swelling), or even death.&nbsp;</span></p>
				<p><strong>Flu Vaccine</strong> can prevent&nbsp; influenza, which spreads easily when an infected person coughs or sneezes. Typical symptoms include a sudden high fever, chills, a dry cough, headache, runny nose, sore throat, and muscle and joint pain. Extreme fatigue can last from days to weeks. Hospitalization or even death among children with chronic diseases, and even among previously healthy children, can occur. Everyone 6 months or older should get the flu vaccine every year.</span></p>
				<p><strong>HPV Vaccine</strong> can prevent human papillomavirus which is common among adolescents and young adults. It is a major cause of cervical cancer in women and genital warts in women and men. HPV is spread through sexual contact. HPV can result in cervical, penile, anal, throat, mouth, vulvar, and vaginal cancer.</span></p>
				<p><strong>MCV Vaccine </strong>can prevent meningococcal diseases, including bacterial meningitis (infection around the brain and spinal cord) and widespread blood infection (sepsis). The bacteria are spread by coughing, sneezing or kissing. Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, sensitivity to light, confusion and sleepiness. About one of every ten people who get the disease dies from it.</span></p>
				<p><em>Adolescents May Also Need Vaccination for:&nbsp;</em></span></p>
				<p><strong>Hepatitis A</strong> is an infection in the liver, which is spread through the fecal-oral route. Symptoms include fever, tiredness, loss of appetite, nausea, abdominal discomfort, dark urine, and jaundice. </span></p>
				<p>An infected person may have no symptoms, a mild illness, or a severe illness for several months.</span>&nbsp;</p>
				<p><strong>Hepatitis B</strong> is an infection of the liver caused by the hepatitis B virus, which is 50 to 100 times more infectious than HIV. The virus is spread through exchange of blood or other body fluids. Symptoms include a flu-like illness with loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, rashes, joint pain,&nbsp; jaundice and may cause liver cancer.</span></p>
				<p><strong>MMR </strong>is a combination vaccine and booster that provides protection for:</span></p>
				<p>Measles</span> is one of the most contagious viral diseases and it is spread by direct contact with the airborne respiratory droplets of an infected person. Symptoms include a rash, fever, cough, and red, watery eyes and can also cause pneumonia, seizures, brain damage, or death.&nbsp;</span></p>
				<p>Mumps</span> is an infectious viral disease spread in the air by a cough or sneeze from an infected person or by coming in contact with a contaminated object, like a toy. The mumps virus causes fever, headaches, painful swelling of the salivary glands under the jaw, fever, muscle aches, tiredness, and loss of appetite.&nbsp;</span></p>
				<p>Rubella</span>, also known as German Measles, is caused by a virus that is spread through coughing and sneezing. Symptoms include fever, swollen glands, and a rash that lasts about three days. Rubella rarely causes serious illness or complications in children, but is very serious for pregnant woman and her fetus.</span></p>
				<p><strong>Polio</strong> is caused by a virus that is spread through contact with the feces (stool) or through droplets from a sneeze or cough. Symptoms typically include sudden fever, sore throat, headache, muscle weakness, and pain. In about one percent of cases, polio can cause paralysis and death.</span></p>
				<p><em>Other disease prevention strategies include:</em></p>
				<ul>
					<li>Regular physical exercise is a disease prevention strategy because it helps reduce risk of heart diseases, various cancers, and muscular- and skeletal diseases.</li>
					<li>Eating plenty of fruits and vegetables each day may reduce the risk of heart disease.</li>
					<li>Good oral health care (fluoride therapy and tooth cleaning), both at home and by a professional, prevents cavities, gum disease (gingivitis), tooth loss, and oral cancers.</li>
					<li>Condoms are sometimes referred to as &ldquo;prophylactics&rdquo; because they prevent pregnancy and sexually transmitted infections.</li>
				</ul>
				<p><em>To learn more about vaccines and other disease prevention strategies:</em></p>
				<ul>
					<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/who/teens/index.html">Centers for Disease Control</a></li>
					<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.adolescentvaccination.org/">National Foundation for Infectious Disease</a></li>
				</ul>
				
