				<h2>Nutrition and Physical Activity</h2>
				<p>Good nutrition and physical activity are essential to overall health and wellbeing. For decades, people have been flooded with messages about how regular exercise and healthy eating prevent diabetes, cancer, and heart disease, but studies have shown that a vast majority of Americans do not follow this advice.&nbsp;</p>
				<p>As a young person, you have an edge. If you are active and eating right, keep it up. These good habits will help you live a healthier, happier life. If you are needing to make some changes---increase your physical activity or add more vegetables to your diet---making them now is easier than later in life when it is sometimes more difficult to change.&nbsp;</p>
				<p><em>Obesity</em></p>
				<p>Obesity is a dangerous condition becoming more and more common in our culture. It is developing into a serious crisis in the teen population. The number of obese teenagers (aged 12 to 19 years) increased from 10.5 to 15.5 percent between 1988 and 2000. Obesity poses a threat to overall health, and is linked to heart disease, high blood pressure, Type 2 diabetes, and even some cancers.</p>
				<p>Overweight adolescents and their parents must understand this is more than a cosmetic issue. Excess weight can have a long-term effect on your adult life and health.&nbsp;</p>
				<p>Obesity as a chronic health problem has received more attention lately. Lawsuits have recently been filed against major fast food corporations serving high fat foods. On average, urban kids under the age of 17 visit fast food restaurants twice a week. Quick service, convenience, good taste and inexpensive prices are appealing to adolescents. Teens can afford to eat and socialize at these places. However, eating fast food too often can lead to rapid weight gain.&nbsp;</p>
				<p>Part of growing up and becoming more independent involves making food choices on your own. With school, hobbies and after-school jobs, teens may spend a lot of time away from home. Still, it is important to eat on a regular schedule. It is thought that up to half of teens skip breakfast. Without breakfast, it is hard to stay awake and concentrate in school. Total nutrient intakes are lower in adolescents who miss breakfast. Breakfast may be skipped in a misguided attempt to reduce calories. Overeating at the next meal or snacking on high calorie and fat foods is often the result. What&rsquo;s more, kids who eat at least two consistent meals a day are leaner than those who do not. Those who eat more family meals also tend to be a normal weight and have better overall nutrition.</p>
				<p>The teen years are a time for learning to make wise food decisions. If poor eating habits are formed now, it is very difficult to acquire better habits later. Those who eat badly during adolescence risk obesity later in life. If eating well is unfamiliar and difficult for you, get one-on-one help by talking to a dietitian.</p>
				<p><em>Poor Nutrition and a Lack of Exercise Contribute to Chronic Disease</em></p>
				<p>Despite decades of research and a flood of messages, childhood obesity has more than tripled in the last 30 years, and today, nearly half of Chicago&rsquo;s youth are overweight or obese.<sup>1</sup> The scientific explanation is a caloric imbalance &ndash; too few calories expended for the amount consumed. However, genetic, behavioral, and environmental factors are also contributing factors.</p>
				<p>There&rsquo;s reason to be concerned about what you eat and how often you exercise. Rates of pre-diabetes and type 2 diabetes among adolescents are skyrocketing.<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;</p>
				<p>If you are 10 years of age and older and have a body mass index greater than the 85th percentile and have at least two other risk factors, such as family history, race/ethnicity, high blood pressure, and acanthosis nigricans (velvety dark skin changes of the neck, armpit, and groin), you should get screened.<sup>4</sup> By identifying pre-diabetes before it progresses to type 2 diabetes you can make healthy changes now and prevent a life-long chronic illness and devastating complications.</p>
				<p><em>To learn more about obesity and how to maintain a healthy weight:</em></p>
				<ul>
				<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.cdc.gov/healthyyouth/npao/index.htm">Centers for Disease Control</a></li>
				<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003101.htm">The National Institutes of Health</a></li>
				</ul>
				<p><em>Change Doesn&rsquo;t Have To Be Overwhelming:</em></p>
				<ul>
				<li>Little changes over time add up. You don&rsquo;t have to become a marathon runner or Olympic swimmer to be fit. You just have to move 30 minutes a day. That&rsquo;s all it takes!</li>
				<li>Good food---fruits, vegetables, lean meats, and whole grains---are not just good for your heart and good for maintaining a healthy weight, it helps makes your brain work better.&nbsp;</li>
				<li>A healthy diet and regular physical activity are great stress-busters and wellbeing boosters!</li>
				</ul>
				<p><em>To learn more about nutrition and physical activity:</em></p>
				<ul>
				<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.choosemyplate.gov/">Choose My Plate</a></li>
