			<h2>Asthma</h2>
			<p>For people with asthma, breathing can be a daily challenge. Asthma is a condition where the bronchial 
			tubes (the tubes that bring air into your lungs) become inflamed making it difficult for air to pass through.
			While breathing, air comes in through the mouth or nose and then travels through the trachea (or wind 
			pipe). The air eventually makes its way to the bronchial tubes, then to the lungs, and then gets pushed 
			back out through the mouth and nose. If the bronchial tubes become inflamed, they produce large 
			quantities of mucus and their airways become blocked much easier. When this happens, you may 
			experience an asthma flare-up, also known as an asthma attack.
			
			<p>Although science understands how an asthma attack happens, it does not know why people develop 
			asthma to begin with. Asthma can be inherited, or passed down through the family genes, it could also be 
			a result of exposure to environmental factors: it is most likely a combination between the two. Either way,
			it is not contagious so you can’t catch it from students in your class or friends around your neighborhood. 
			<p>Also, the flare-ups that people with asthma experience can be triggered by many different things. It is 
			important to pay close attention to what triggers your asthma so that you can avoid those situations and 
			lead a healthier life. Some common triggers are:
			<ul>
			<li>Allergens like dust, mold, pollen, and animal dander.
			<li>Pollutants in the air such as smoke, smog, dust, perfumes, paint, and gasoline.
			<li>Exercise: although this can be frustrating if you want to engage in sports, consulting with a doctor
			can help you discover medication that can aid you in engaging in the activities you enjoy. Your 
			asthma shouldn’t discourage you from being physically active. Many athletes have asthma and 
			work hard to control their condition to stay active.
			<li>Cold and dry air, as well as extreme heat and humidity.
			<li>Other illnesses: for instance, colds, flus, strep throat, and other viruses.</ol>
			<p>There is no cure for asthma, but having it is not the end of the world. You can still lead a healthy, 
			productive life. Asthma is very manageable by educating yourself on the condition, avoiding 
			environments and activities that trigger your asthma, and through medication.     
				 <p>There are two primary types of asthma medication: rescue medications and controller medications. 
			Rescue medications act very quickly and help you get through an asthma attack as it is happening. These medicines are given orally with an inhaler and open up the blocked airways to allow air to get through. 
			<p>The other medications, known as controller medications, are not for immediate relief but try to treat the medicines 
			act very slowly and often take a week or more to start helping. 
			<p>Along with the medicine that you take, it is very important for you, your healthcare
			provider, and your parents to put together an asthma action plan. You should share
			this plan with your teachers and school nurse. This plan is critical to your health
			because it clearly lays out instructions for what should be done in case you have an
			asthma attack. This is important because asthma attacks are specific to each person
			who experiences it in a different way. This plan will detail when you should take
			your medication, how much medication should be taken, and the difference
			between when a doctor needs to be called and when you need to go to the emergency room. 
			<p>Your action plan should have other important information such as: emergency phone numbers, a list of 
			triggers and how to avoid them and the names of your medications and how much too normally take. 
			While talking about this with your doctor and parents you may discover other information to put on your asthma action plan. 
			<p><i>To learn more about asthma:</i>
			<ul>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.aaaai.org/conditions-andtreatments/just-for-kids.aspx">American Academy of Allergy Asthma & Immunology</a>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.lung.org/lung-disease/asthma/">American Lung Association</a>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.lungchicago.org/asthma/">Respiratory Health Association</a>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.asthmaeducationcenter.net/">Asthma Education Center</a>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.chcs.org/publications3960/publications_show.htm?
			doc_id=413823">Center for Health Care Strategies</a>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.cdc.gov/asthma/">Center for Disease Control</a>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://kidshealth.org/kid/asthma_basics/what/asthma.html">Kids Health</a>
			</ul>
			<p><i>Asthma Resources in Spanish</i>
			<ul><li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.cdc.gov/spanish/enfermedades/asma.html">Center for Disease Control: Spanish Translation</a>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/spanish/asthma.html">MedlinePlus</a>
