  	<div id="section1" class="tpad">
    	<div class="row">
      		<div class="ten columns offset-by-one">
      		<h2>Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)</h2>
			<p>Sometimes it is hard to concentrate, especially if the television is turned on, kids are playing in other parts
			of the room, or your parents are making dinner while you’re studying. Sometimes people can have a 
			really hard time sitting still, focusing, and paying attention even if nothing else is going on in the room. This is sometimes caused by attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, or ADHD. ADHD is a general 
			disorder that can affect each person differently. Some signs are:</p>
			<ul><li>Problems staying focused.</li>
			<li>Difficulty finishing assignments.</li>
			<li>Trouble following instructions.</li>
			<li>Loses things such as homework.</li>
			<li>Easily distracted, even while engaged in fun activities.</li>
			<li>Trouble with attention to detail.</li>
			<li>Struggles with organizing activities.</li>
			<li>Finds it hard to wait their turn.</li>
			<li>Interrupts others before they are finished speaking.</li>
			<li>Fidgets with hands or feet.</li>
			<li>Talks rapidly and moves on before others respond.</li>
			</ul>
			<p>Nobody actually knows what causes ADHD. Some doctors think it is genetic, or passed down through the
			family. It is often found in children born prematurely and in boys more than girls. Doctors do know that 
			low amounts of dopamine, a chemical in the brain that helps with attention, leads to a greater chance of 
			ADHD.</p>
			<p>Since ADHD affects everyone differently, there is no cure for it and treatment is given differently to each 
			person who is affected. Sometimes people with ADHD are given medication that helps them concentrate 
			and stay focused. This medicine also can help you stay calm and usually only needs to be taken once a 
			day. Sometimes it is good to talk to a counselor on a regular basis. You may also go see this counselor 
			with your family. This is so that your family can learn how they can best help you and so they can stay 
			informed about how ADHD is affecting you. Sometimes schools will put together a plan for your teachers
			to follow while you are in class with them, so that they can better help you learn at school.</p>
			<p>There are things you can do to help with your ADHD. You can sit in the front of the class so that there are
			fewer distractions during school. Turn off the TV while studying or reading. Talk with a teacher or parent 
			if you are having trouble concentrating or focusing. Keep all your school supplies and important 
			documents at home organized. Get lots of exercise and take short breaks while doing schoolwork. Talk to 
			your friends about what having ADHD means. Stay positive!</p>
			<ul><li>Accept your diagnosis: You don’t have ADHD because of anything you did wrong; it simply 
			is the way your brain is wired.</li>
			<li>Practice self-care: sometimes people who have ADHD can become concentrated on a task 
			and forget to take care of themselves. Plan breaks throughout the day to stop and ask yourself
			if you need anything at the moment, perhaps to eat, take a nap, sleep for the night, or move on
			to a different task. </li>
			<li>Be sure to get plenty of sleep.</li>
			<li>Use pill containers to ensure proper dosage and to track if you have already taken your 
			medication for the day.</li>
			<li>Practice self-control: People with ADHD are at a higher risk for addiction. Keep yourself 
			interested in stimulating activities, such as art, music, dancing, etc.</li> 
			<li>Keep a notebook: ADHD often times causes people to day-dream and/or forget conversations 
			and thoughts. Keeping a journal or notebook and writing down thoughts you have and people 
			you meet will help you remember your ideas.</li> 
			<li>Keep a planner: be sure to write down all your daily events and appointments.</li>
			<li>Set alarms: keep yourself on time by setting your bedroom alarm, or alarms on a cell phone to
			help you keep track of your daily activities.</li>
			<li>Just say no: Many who have ADHD are very kind, caring individuals who often become 
			overstressed due to their willingness to please others. Be conscious about how many people 
			you have agreed to help. When others ask for your help, let them know you’ll think about it 
			to give yourself time to consider the implications of it.</li>
			<li>Seek support: Don’t be afraid to ask a parent, doctor, or teacher for help. If you’re having 
			trouble focusing in school, speak with your teachers to see if a plan can be developed to 
			facilitate your learning environment.</li></ul>
			<p><i>To learn more about ADHD</i></p>
			<ul><li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/adhd/DS00275">Mayo Clinic</a></li>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://kidshealth.org/teen/school_jobs/school/adhd.html">TeensHealth</a></li>
