	<div id="section2" class="tpad">
		<div class="row">
			<div class="ten columns offset-by-one">
			<h2>Diabetes</h2>
			<p>Diabetes affects your body&rsquo;s ability to produce or use glucose (sugar). More and more young people are being diagnosed with diabetes. If you have this condition, or are at risk for developing diabetes, you need to take action now to safeguard your health. &nbsp;</p>
			<p>Glucose is the fuel that powers your body and it&rsquo;s in nearly everything we eat---fruits, vegetables, breads----not just candies and sodas. To get glucose into the cells, your body produced insulin. Insulin is a hormone that works like a doorman, allowing glucose to enter into your cells and energize you.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>But when a person has diabetes, either the insulin isn&rsquo;t doing the job that it should (Type 2 diabetes) or the body doesn&rsquo;t make any insulin at all (Type 1 diabetes). With both types of diabetes, too much sugar can build up in the blood, which will make you very sick damage your eyesight, your kidneys, your heart, and circulation, which can lead to amputations.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>There is another big difference between Type 1 and Type 2 Diabetes. Type 1 diabetes cannot be prevented. Scientists don&rsquo;t know what causes diabetes but they think that both genes and the environment are factors. It&rsquo;s an autoimmune disease that shuts down your pancreas so you no longer make insulin.&nbsp; People with type I diabetes will have to take insulin with every meal, every day to stay alive. &nbsp;</p>
			<p>Type 2 Diabetes usually develops in people who are overweight and who don&rsquo;t exercise. Extra weight and an inactive lifestyle make it harder for insulin to work properly. It is possible to prevent Type 2 diabetes by getting plenty of exercise and eating healthy foods. Here are some steps you can take to help prevent Type 2 diabetes:</p>
			<ol>
			<li>Eat plenty of fruits, vegetables, and proteins</li>
			<li>Make your calories count. Keep your intake of sugary, refined, starchy, and fatty foods to a minimum.</li>
			<li>Decrease your soda intake. Did you know that people who drink a soda every day are more at risk for developing Type 2 than a person who is overweight?</li>
			<li>Make fewer trips to fast food restaurants&nbsp;</li>
			<li>Exercise every day. Just 30 minutes a day is enough to protect your health. Playing sports is a great way to stay healthy!</li>
			<li>Talk with your parents, your teachers, and your healthcare provider about your physical health and what you can do to maintain a healthy lifestyle.</li>
			</ol>
			<p>But Type 2 diabetes isn&rsquo;t just about how much a person weighs or what kind of food they eat (or don&rsquo;t eat). Genetics plays a role, too. For example, skinny people can get Type 2 diabetes and African Americans and Hispanic people face higher risks for developing Type 2.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>Many students with diabetes manage their condition independently. However, if a person&rsquo;s blood sugar level drops too low, they may require emergency medication called Glucagon.&nbsp;</p>
			<p><em>To learn more about diabetes</em></p>
