			<h2>Epilepsy/Seizure Disorder</h2>
			<p>Epilepsy/seizure disorder is more common that most people realize. About one person in a hundred lives with this disorder, which often begins in childhood. It is a disorder, not a disease; it&rsquo;s not something you &ldquo;catch&rdquo; by being around a person with this disorder.<strong>&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;</p>
			<p>Epilepsy /seizure disorder is not a mental disorder. It is a physical disorder formed by sudden or brief changes in how the brain works. It is a symptom of a neurological disorder that affects the brain and shows itself in the form of seizures.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>A seizure occurs when the normal electrical balance in the brain is lost. The brain's nerve cells fall through; they either ignite when they shouldn't or don't ignite when they should. The result is a sudden, brief, uncontrolled rush of abnormal electrical activity in the brain. Seizures are the physical effects of such unusual bursts of electrical energy in the brain. These overactive signals may keep the brain from understanding what the eyes see. The person may stare during a seizure, or they may affect leg muscle tone and cause a person to fall down. The type of seizure depends on how many cells are launched and which area of the brain is involved. A seizure may be a change in behavior, consciousness, movement, perception and or sensation.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>Drugs don&rsquo;t cure epilepsy/seizure disorder, but they often reduce or even stop seizures from occurring by altering the activity of neurons in the brain. Most students achieve seizure control with medication. Sometimes, though, a student will experience what&rsquo;s called a &ldquo;break-through&rdquo; seizure, which is <span class="s7">a bout of seizure activity that requires immediate emergency attention, including medication called DiaStat.</p>
			<p><em>To learn more about epilepsy/seizure disorders</em>&nbsp;</p>
			<ul>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.epilepsyfoundation.org">Epilepsy Foundation</a></li>
			<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.ninds.nih.gov/disorders/epilepsy/epilepsy.htm">National Institute of National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke</a></li>
			</ul>
