			<h2>Food Allergies</h2>
			<p>Food Allergies are becoming more and more common for children and adolescents.&nbsp; It is estimated that about 3 million kids in the US have food allergies and it is constantly growing.&nbsp; Food allergies are very serious and unfortunately can be fatal for some people. It is a condition that needs to be taken very seriously.</p>
			<p>A food allergy is different than food intolerance. Some key facts about food allergy:</p>
			<ul>
			<li>Food allergy is an overreaction of the immune system to a food protein. Allergic reactions will happen each and every time you eat that food.&nbsp; Reactions will happen fast- within minutes to 2 hours.</li>
			<li>It may take only a tiny or even a miniscule amount of food to cause a reaction.&nbsp; For example, if someone touches something they are allergic to, and then they rub their nose or eyes, open areas of skin or put their hands in their mouth, this could be enough to cause a reaction.</li>
			<li>The severity and progress of an allergic reaction is <span class="s1">unpredictable: a mild reaction can become severe within minutes.&nbsp; Reactions can be different for everyone, and reactions can even be different each time for the same person &ndash; very unpredictable!&nbsp; For this reason, all allergic symptoms a person has with food allergy must be taken very seriously. All food allergies are potentially life threatening.&nbsp;</li>
			</ul>
			<p>The top 8 most common food allergies are:</p>
			<p><img src="images/food_stuff.png"></p>
		
			<p><em>Ways to treat food allergies:</em></p>
			<p>Unfortunately, there is no cure for food allergies, but for some people they will grow out of certain food allergies during their lifetime.&nbsp; Everyone can develop a food allergy at some point in his or her life.&nbsp; Just because you didn&rsquo;t get one when you were young doesn&rsquo;t mean you can develop one as a teenager or adult.&nbsp;</p>
			<p><em>The best way to manage and treat food allergies is by:</em>&nbsp;</p>
			<ul>
			<li>Preventing Reactions &ndash; avoiding the foods that you are allergic too and cross contamination with those foods. Read food labels and always make sure you know exactly what you are going to eat</li>
			<li>Recognize reactions &ndash; take all allergic reactions seriously (see examples in picture below)</li>
			<li>Respond to reactions &ndash; don&rsquo;t minimize symptoms, wait, or think they&rsquo;ll just go away. Act quickly. The motto is: If it&rsquo;s more than skin, stick it in. In other words, if a person other symptoms in addition to a rash, they need emergency medication.&nbsp;</li>
			<li>Save a life. Use an Epinephrine Auto Injector (EpiPen) and call 911.&nbsp;</li>
			</ul>
