 	 <div id="section6" class="tpad">
		<div class="row">
			<div class="ten columns offset-by-one">     
			<h2>Sickle Cell Anemia</h2>

			<p>It may seem strange, but inside your blood are tiny little cells called red blood cells. What is even crazier, these red blood cells are actually made in your bones! Every time you breathe, bone marrow creates red blood cells and releases them into your blood to carry oxygen throughout your body. Oxygen is really important for your body, and these red blood cells are usually rounded since it is the easiest way for them to move through your blood stream. Sometimes a person doesn&rsquo;t have enough red blood cells. This is called anemia. It means that people who have anemia have less oxygen throughout their body. Sometimes anemia is caused because the red blood cells are not round but sickle shaped. A sickle shape looks like a crescent moon. When a person has sickle shaped red blood cells, it is called sickle cell anemia. &nbsp;</p>
			<p>The problem with sickle cell anemia is that the sickle-shaped red blood cells do not move as easily through the blood stream. They can become stuck and make it hard for blood to flow through the body. This can cause pain in the bones, and can be dangerous to organs that need a constant supply of blood, like the brain, heart, and kidneys. The body knows to destroy the sickle cells, but it can do so quicker than the body can make new blood cells. This causes anemia.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>If you have sickle cell anemia you may feel pain in your chest, stomach, or bones when blood gets blocked because of sickle shaped cells. This pain may last a few minutes or even a couple of days; it might hurt a lot or just a little. Nobody can tell when this pain might happen, it all depends on if a sickle cell gets stuck. However, being too cold, getting sick, and not drinking enough fluids can make it happen more often. Also, if you have sickle cell anemia, you may get tired easily or become sick more often than other children. You may also not grow as fast as your friends and classmates.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>Sickle cell anemia is not a disease you can catch or pass on to your friends or family. It is genetic, which means it is passed down from being born into a family that has had that disease before. A doctor can find out if you have sickle cell anemia by doing special blood tests. These tests will let the doctor look at hemoglobin, a part of the blood that carries oxygen throughout the body inside the red blood cells. If the doctor finds the right kind of hemoglobin, it means they have discovered sickle cell anemia in the blood.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>To help with sickle cell anemia, a doctor may prescribe penicillin. Doctors may also have you take a vitamin called folic acid, which helps the body make new red blood cells. Although these medicines will not cure sickle cell anemia, they will help you stay healthy and prevent sickness that would increase the chance of sickle cells becoming stuck. The doctor may also give you pain medicine to help you feel better when it does happen. If the pain is too much or lasts too long, you may go to the hospital for antibiotics or more pain medicine. In some cases, you may go to the hospital for a blood transfusion. This is when the doctor puts healthy blood cells into your body, which makes it easier for the blood to flow and carry the oxygen you need.&nbsp;</p>
			<p>Not only will taking the penicillin and vitamins help you stay healthy and feel less pain, but so will eating healthy foods and drinks, and sleeping well. You can also play and exercise, but remember to not get too hot, cold, or tired. Talk with your parents and doctor about good activities you can do every day to help you stay healthy. Remember that if you feel any pain or have a fever, tell an adult right away. The sooner you get help the faster you can feel well.</p>
			<p><em>To learn more about Sickle Cell Anemia:</em></p>
